item.title: New Ebola Cases Found in Congo
item.description: The Democratic Republic of Congo’s health ministry reported a fresh cluster of Ebola infections in the country’s northwest.

item.title: Output Decline at Factories Eases, But Recovery Set to Be Slow
item.description: Factories in the U.S. and abroad continued to reduce output and shed jobs last month, though the pace of deterioration moderated as governments moved to ease coronavirus-related restrictions on their economies.

item.title: Russia Sets July 1 Vote on Constitution Changes Allowing Putin to Extend His Rule
item.description: A vote on changes to Russia’s constitution that could potentially allow President Vladimir Putin to maintain his grip on power for years to come will be held on July 1.

item.title: Hong Kong Police Ban Tiananmen Massacre Vigil
item.description: Police denied an application by organizers of an annual candlelight vigil to commemorate the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, amid concerns over civil liberties after China said it would impose national-security legislation on the city.

item.title: Coronavirus Prods the U.K. to Consider the Once-Unthinkable: Negative Rates
item.description: The economic fallout from the coronavirus pandemic is whittling away the Bank of England’s long-held aversion to subzero rates, in the latest example of how the scale of the Covid-19 crisis is pushing central banks and governments deep into new policy territory.

item.title: China's Barely Begun Economic Recovery Shows Signs of Stalling
item.description: More and more Chinese factories have reopened for work in the past three months as authorities have eased their once-aggressive coronavirus measures. But now they are facing the dire reality of falling orders from overseas customers.
